{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":30326,"record_hash":"sha256:df955212b28b1657cbd87c2712e7bffc464e23e36446c9973c73cd354b4f8263","timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:55:42.696Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes, that makes sense.\n\nFor `but agentlog sync`, missing remote ref should mean “first sync,” not an error.\n\nSo the behavior should be:\n\n```text\nremote exists, refs/meta/agentlog exists:\n  fetch, materialize, serialize, push with retry\n\nremote exists, refs/meta/agentlog missing:\n  skip/soft-fail fetch for that ref\n  serialize local agentlog scope\n  push refs/meta/local/agentlog -> refs/meta/agentlog\n  this creates the remote ref\n\nremote itself missing/unreachable:\n  fail clearly\n```\n\nThat fits Git’s normal push semantics: pushing a local ref to a nonexistent remote ref creates it, as long as permissions allow it.\n\nThe only thing to be careful about is materialization isolation. If the remote ref is absent, we should not treat that as “remote has empty metadata” and delete or tombstone anything locally. It should mean “no incoming agentlog metadata yet.”\n\nI’d encode that in the design note as: **missing agentlog remote ref is an initial sync state and must not materialize emptiness.**","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:55:42.696Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}